(foul ground) an area over which it is safe to navigate but which should be avoided for anchoring, taking the ground or ground fishing. (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4)
wreck of which only the mast(s) is visible at the sounding datum indicated.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: wreck showing any portion of hull or superstructure
ExpectedValue.Definition: wreck of which any portion of the hull or superstructure is visible at the sounding datum indicated.

Attribute.Name: Category of zone of confidence in data

ExpectedValue.Meaning: zone of confidence U (data not assessed)

ExpectedValue.Definition: S expanded or condensed to fit between the first and last positions.
character spacing in accordance with the typeface in use.

Attribute.Name: Character specification
Attribute.References: INT 1: not specified; M-4: not specified;

Attribute.Name: Colour
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for all LIGHTS objects, except air obstruction lights or fog detector lights.

Attribute.Name: Colour pattern
Attribute.Condition: Mandatory for ANY OBJECT that has more than one colour.

ExpectedValue.Definition: straight bands or stripes of differing colours painted horizontally.
straight bands or stripes of differing colours painted vertically.
straight bands or stripes of differing colours painted diagonally (ie not horizontally or vertically).
often referred to as checker plate, where alternate colours are used to create squares similar to a chess or draught board. The platform may be straight or diagonal.
straight bands or stripes of differing colours painted in an unknown direction.
a band or stripe of colour which is displayed around the outer edge of the object which may also form a border to an inner pattern or plain colour.

Attribute.Name: Communication channel
Attribute.Definition: A channel number assigned to a specific radio frequency, frequencies or frequency band.
Attribute.Indication: Each VHF-channel should be indicated in square brackets by 2 digits and up to 2 characters (A-Z) ; e.g. VHF channel 7 -> [07], VHF channel 16 -> [16]

Attribute.Name: Compass size
Attribute.Definition: specifies the display radius for a cartographic compass rose.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: millimetre (mm) Resolution: 0.1 mm

Attribute.Name: Compilation date
Attribute.Definition: The date on which the compilation of the data was completed.
Attribute.Indication: The compilation data should be encoded using 4 digits for the year (CCYY), 2 digits for the month (MM) (e.g. April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specific month and/or day is required/known, indication of the month and/or day is omitted. This conforms to ISO 8601:1988.

Attribute.Name: Compilation scale
Attribute.Definition: The scale at which the data was originally compiled.
Attribute.Indication: The modulus of the scale is indicated, that is 1:75 000 is encoded as 75000. Unit: none Resolution: 1
Attribute.Remarks: For example, the scale of the paper chart that was used for the ENC compilation. This attribute is only used in conjunction with the meta-object 'Compilation Scale of data ' (M_CSCL) which is used to define polygons of equal compilation scale. CSCALE should therefore not be confused with the attributes SCAMIN and SCAMAX.

Attribute.Name: Condition
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'condition' encodes the various conditions of buildings and other constructions. The default 'condition' should be considered to be completed, undamaged and working normally. This attribute should, therefore, only be used to indicate objects whose condition is anything other than 'normal'.

ExpectedValue.Definition: a structure that is in the process of being built.
a structure in a decayed or deteriorated condition, resulting from neglect or disuse; or a damaged structure in need of repair. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4456).
an area of the sea that is being reclaimed as land, usually by the dumping of earth and other material.
a windmill or windmotor from which the turbine blades are missing.
an area where future construction is planned.
an object which returns a strong radar echo. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4142).
an object which does not return a particularly strong radar echo.
an object which returns a strong radar echo, having a radar reflector.
term applied to an object either natural or artificial which is distinctly and notably visible from seaward. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 984)
an object which is visible from seaward, but is not conspicuous.

Attribute.Name: Current velocity
Attribute.Definition: The rate of travel of a current.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: knot (kt); Resolution: 0.1kt
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'current velocity' indicates the speed of the current in knots.

Attribute.Name: Date end
Attribute.Indication: The ‘date end’ should be encoded using 4 digits for the year (CCYY), 2 digits for the month (MM) (e.g. April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specific month and/or day is required/known, indication of the month and/or day is omitted. This conforms to ISO 8601:1988.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'date end' indicates the latest date on which an object (e.g. a buoy) will be present. This attribute is to be used to indicate the removal or cancellation of an object at a specific date in the future. See also 'periodic date end'.

Attribute.Name: Date start
Attribute.Indication: The ‘date start’ should be encoded using 4 digits for the year (CCYY), 2 digits for the month (MM) (e.g. April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specific month and/or day is required/known, indication of the month and/or day is omitted. This conforms to ISO 8601:1988.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'date, start' indicates the earliest date on which an object (e.g. a buoy) will be present. This attribute is to be used to indicate the deployment or implementation of an object at a specific date in the future. See also 'periodic date start'.

Attribute.Name: Depth range value 1
Attribute.Definition: The minimum (shoalest) value of a depth range.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the DUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the DUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 fm or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Remarks: Where the area dries, the value is negative.
Attribute.Format: sxxxxx.x; s: sign, negative values only.

Attribute.Name: Depth range value 2
Attribute.Definition: The maximum (deepest) value of a depth range.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the DUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the DUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 fm or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Remarks: Where the area dries, the value is negative.
Attribute.Format: sxxxxx.x; s: sign, negative values only.

ExpectedValue.Definition: depths are specified in metres (SI units of length).
depths are specified in fathoms (units of six feet of depth) and feet.
depths are specified in feet (imperial units of length).
depths are specified in fathoms (units of six feet of depth) and fractions of fathoms.

Attribute.Name: Elevation
Attribute.Definition: The altitude of the ground level of an object, measured from a specified vertical datum.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft

Attribute.Name: Estimated range of transmission
Attribute.Definition: The estimated range of a non-optical electromagnetic transmission.
Attribute.References: INT 1: none specified; M-4: none specified;
Attribute.Indication: Unit: nautical mile (M); Resolution: 0.1M
Attribute.Remarks: The estimated range (distance) assumes 'in vacuo' transmission and a standard antenna height of 5 metres. Thus it gives a hint to the mariner whether he is likely to receive transmission at a certain distance from an object carrying this attribute.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: light shown without change of character
ExpectedValue.Definition: a light shown throughout the 24 hours without change of character. (IHO Chart specifications, M-4)
a light which is only exhibited by day.
a light which is exhibited in fog or conditions of reduced visibility.
a light which is only exhibited at night.

Attribute.Name: Exposition of sounding
Attribute.Remarks: This attribute indicates objects with a 'value of sounding' not within the range of depth of the surrounding depth area. These objects could be a potential danger for navigation.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: within the range of depth of surrounding depth area
ExpectedValue.Definition: the depth corresponds to the depth range of the surrounding depth area. i.e. the depth is not shoaler than the minimum depth of the surrounding depth area or deeper than the maximum depth of the surrounding depth area.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: shoaler than range of depth of surrounding depth area
ExpectedValue.Definition: the depth is shoaler than the minimum depth of the surrounding depth area.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: deeper than range of depth of surrounding depth area
ExpectedValue.Definition: the depth is deeper than the maximum depth of the surrounding depth area.
the office of the local official who has charge of mooring and berthing of vessels, collecting harbour fees, etc. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2191).
an office which is charged with enforcing customs regulations.
the office which is charged with the administration of health laws and sanitary inspections. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
an institution or establishment providing medical or surgical treatment for the ill or wounded. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
the public department, agency or organisation responsible primarily for the collection, transmission and distribution of mail. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
an establishment, especially of a comfortable or luxurious kind, where paying visitors are provided with accommodation, meals and other services. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
a building with platforms where trains arrive, load, discharge and depart. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
the office of the local police force.
the headquarters of a local water-police force.
the office or headquarters of pilots; the place where the services of a pilot may be obtained. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3845)
a distinctive structure on shore from which personnel keep watch upon events at sea or along the coast. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2917)
an office for custody, deposit, load, exchange or issue of money. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
the quarters of an executive officer (director, manager, etc.) with responsibility for an administrative area.
a building or part of a building for storage of wares or goods. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
a building or buildings with equipment for manufacturing; a workshop. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)

a stationary plant containing apparatus for large scale conversion of some form of energy (such as hydraulic, steam, chemical or nuclear energy) into electrical energy. (McGraw-Hill Dictionary of Scientific and Technical Terms, 3rd Edition, 1984)
a building for the management of affairs. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
a building concerned with education (eg. school, college, university, etc.).
a building for public Christian worship. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
a building for Christian worship other than a parish, cathedral or church, especially one attached to a private house or institution. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
a building for public Jewish worship. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
a Hindu or Buddhist temple or sacred building. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
a building for public Shinto worship. (adapted from The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
see pagoda.
a Muslim place of worship. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
a shrine marking the burial place of a Muslim holy man. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993)
keeping a watch upon events at sea or along the coast. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2917)
transmitting and/or receiving electronic communication signals. (adapted from Digital Geographic Information Standard -DIGEST)
broadcast of television signals.
broadcast of radio signals.
a method, system or technique of using beamed, reflected and timed radio waves for detecting, locating or tracking objects, and for measuring altitudes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4158)
supporting a light.
broadcasting and receiving signals using microwaves.
dissipating heat.
a place from which the surroundings can be observed but at which a watch is not habitually maintained. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2917)
a visual time signal in form of a ball.
visual time signal (adapted from S-32, 5th Edition, 5536).
used to control the flow of air, rail, or marine traffic. (Digital Geographic Information Standard - DIGEST)
a facility to secure an airship. (adapted from Digital Geographic Information Standard - DIGEST)
a large usually unroofed building with tiers of seats for spectators.
a location at which buses arrive and from which they depart.

Attribute.Name: Height
Attribute.Definition: The value of the vertical distance to the highest point of the object, measured from a specified vertical datum.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Remarks: Height must not be used for floating objects.

Attribute.Name: Height/length units
Attribute.Remarks: his attribute encodes the units of measurement for heights and lengths, but not depths for which the attribute depth units (DUNITS) is used.

ExpectedValue.Definition: heights/lengths are specified in metres (SI units of length).
heights/lengths are specified in feet (imperial units of length).

Attribute.Name: Horizontal accuracy
Attribute.Definition: The best estimate of the horizontal accuracy of horizontal clearance and distances.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Remarks: The expected input is the radius of the two-dimensional error. The error is assumed to be positive and negative. The plus/minus character shall not be encoded.

Attribute.Name: Horizontal clearance
Attribute.Definition: The width of an object, such as a canal or a tunnel, which is available for safe navigation. This may, or may not, be the same as the total physical width of the object.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for GATCON objects if navigable at compilation scale.

Attribute.Name: Horizontal length
Attribute.Definition: A measurement of the longer of two linear axis. (Digital Geographic Information Working Group - DGIWG, Oct. 87)
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft

Attribute.Name: Horizontal width
Attribute.Definition: A measurement of the shorter of two linear axis. (Digital Geographic Information Working Group -DGIWG, Oct 87)
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft

Attribute.Name: Ice factor
Attribute.Definition: The value of the maximum variation in the vertical clearance of an overhead cable due to an accumulation of ice.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft

Attribute.Name: Information
Attribute.Definition: Textual information about the object.
Attribute.Remarks: This attribute should be used, for example, to hold the information that is shown on paper charts by cautionary and explanatory notes. No formatting of text is possible within INFORM. If formatted text is required, then the attribute TXTDSC must be used.
Attribute.Condition: For CTNARE and PRCARE objects, at least one of attributes INFORM or TXTDSC must be encoded For S-57 Edition 3.1.1 ARCSLN, ASLXIS and NEWOBJ objects, and RESARE objects with CATREA=27 or 28, at least one of attributes INFORM or TXTDSC must be encoded.
Attribute.Format: up to 300 characters may be included in this string.

ExpectedValue.Definition: involving more than one country; covering more than one national area.
an area administered or controlled by a single nation.
an area smaller than the nation in which it lies.
position refers to the centre of the text S.
position refers to the right side of the last character in the text S.
position refers to the left side of the first character in the text S.
position refers to the bottom of the text S.
position refers to the centre of the text S.
position refers to the top of the text S.

Attribute.Name: Lifting capacity
Attribute.Definition: The specific safe lifting capacity of an object.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: tonne (t); Resolution: 0.1 t

Attribute.Name: Light characteristic
Attribute.Remarks: A selection of the above characteristics is defined and illustrated diagrammatically in IHO Chart Specifications, M-4, 471.2.
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for all LIGHTS objects, except air obstruction lights or fog detector lights.

ExpectedValue.Definition: a signal light that shows continuously, in any given direction, with constant luminous intensity and colour. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2780)

a rhythmic light in which the total duration of light in a period is clearly shorter than the total duration of darkness and all the appearances of light are of equal duration. It may be : single flashing : a flashing light in which a flash is regularly repeated at a rate of less than 50 flashes per minutes. group flashing : a flashing light in which a group of two or more flashes, which are specified in number, is regularly repeated. composite group flashing : a flashing light in which a sequence of groups of one or more flashes, which are specified in number, is regularly repeated, and the groups comprise different numbers of flashes. (IALA International Dictionary of Aids to Marine Navigation)
a single-flashing light in which an appearance of light of not less than two seconds duration is regularly repeated. (IALA International Dictionary of Aids to Marine Navigation)

a rhythmic light in which flashes are repeated at a rate of not less than 50 flashes per minutes but less than 80 flashes per minutes. It may be : continuous quick-flashing : a quick-flashing light in which a flash is regularly repeated. group quick-flashing : a quick-flashing light in which a group of two or more flashes, which are specified in number, is regularly repeated. (IALA International Dictionary of Aids to Marine Navigation)

a rhythmic light in which flashes are repeated at a rate of not less than 80 flashes per minute but less than 160 flashes per minute. It may be : continuous very quick-flashing : a very quick-flashing light in which a flash is regularly repeated. group very quick-flashing : a very quick-flashing light in which a group of two or more flashes, which are specified in number, is regularly repeated.

Attribute.Name: Sector limit one
Attribute.Definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. (Advanced Learner's Dictionary, 2nd Edition) Sector limit 1 specifies the first limit of the sector. The order of sector limit 1 and sector limit 2 is clockwise around the central object (e.g. a light)
Attribute.Indication: Unit: degree (°); Resolution: 0.01 degree
Attribute.Remarks: The values given to the common limits of adjacent sectors should be identical. The orientation of bearing is from seaward to the central object. This conforms with the method used in 'List of Lights' publications. A generic term such as 'to shore' cannot be used; a specific bearing must be encoded. Where a light sector limit is defined as 'to the shore', it should be encoded using a value that ensures that, when the limit is drawn, it will fall entirely on land.
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for LIGHTS objects that are sector lights.

Attribute.Name: Sector limit two
Attribute.Definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. (Advanced Learner's Dictionary, 2nd Edition) The sector limit 2 specifies the second limit of the sector. The order of sector limit 1 and sector limit 2 is clockwise around the central object (e.g. a light)
Attribute.Indication: Unit: degree (°); Resolution: 0.01 degree
Attribute.Remarks: The values given to the common limits of adjacent sectors should be identical. The orientation of bearing is from seaward to the central object. This to the method used in 'List of Lights' publications. A generic term such as 'to shore' cannot be used; a specific bearing must be encoded. Where a light sector limit is defined as 'to the shore', it should be encoded using a value that ensures that, when the limit is drawn, it will fall entirely on land.
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for LIGHTS objects that are sector lights.

Attribute.Name: Shift parameters
Attribute.Definition: Latitude and longitude offsets required to shift a position from one geodetic datum to another.
Attribute.Indication: Lat: Shift parameter in latitude from the specified h orizontal datum to the horizontal datum of the data. Unit: minutes ('), negative south. Resolution: 0.001 minute; Lon: Shift parameter in longitude from the specified horizontal datum to the horizontal datum of the data. Unit: Resolution minutes ('), negative west. Resolution: 0.001 minute
Attribute.Remarks: All necessary information for conversion of geographic coordinates from most of the Geodetic Datums in the above list to WGS-84 is contained in the "User's Handbook on Datum Transformations involving WGS-84", prepared by the US Defense Mapping Agency and which is available from the IHB as IHO Publication S-60 (English and French Versions), along with an associated standard datum transformation software on floppy disk called "MADTRAN". The resulting latitude and longitude offsets can be encoded in the attribute SHIPAM. Additional information on the transformation as indicated in IHO Publication S-60, e.g. TOY-M (Mean Solution), TOY-A (Japan), TOY-B (South Korea) or TOY-C (Okinawa) in relation to Tokyo Datum, may be encoded in the attribute INFORM or NINFORM.
Attribute.Format: sxx.xxx, syy.yyy; sxx.xxx: lat; syy.yyy: lon; s: sign, negative values only.

Attribute.Name: Survey date - start
Attribute.Definition: The start date of the survey.
Attribute.Indication: The 'survey date, start' should be encoded using 4 digits for the calendar year (CCYY), 2 digits for the month (MM) (e.g. April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specific month and/or day is required/known, indication of the month and/or the day is omitted. This conforms to ISO8601: 1988.
Attribute.Format: CCYYMMDD (full date, mandatory);CCYYMM (no specific day required, mandatory); CCYY (no specific month required, mandatory)

ExpectedValue.Definition: a survey made to a lower degree of accuracy and detail than the chosen scale would normally indicate. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 5219)
a thorough survey usually conducted with reference to guidelines.
a survey principally aimed at the investigation of underwater obstructions and dangers.
a survey where soundings are acquired by vessels on passage.
a survey where features have been positioned and delimited using remote sensing techniques.

Attribute.Name: Symbol scaling factor
Attribute.Definition: a scaling factor relative to the standard symbol size.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: none; Resolution: 0.1

ExpectedValue.Definition: the depth was determined by using an instrument that determines depth of water by measuring the time interval between emission of a sonic or ultrasonic signal and return of its echo from the bottom. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 1547)

the depth was computed from a record produced by active sonar in which fixed acoustic beams are directed into the water perpendicularly to the direction of travel to scan the bottom and generate a record of the bottom configuration. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 4710)
the depth was determined by using a wide swath echo sounder that uses multiple beams to measure depths directly below and transverse to the ship's track. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 3339)
the depth was determined by a person skilled in the practice of diving. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 1422)
the depth was determined by using a line, graduated with attached marks and fastened to a sounding lead. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 2698)

the given area was determined to be free from navigational dangers to a certain depth by towing a buoyed wire at the desired epth by two launches, or a least depth was identified using the same technique. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5248, 6013)

the depth was determined by using an instrument that measures distance by emitting timed pulses of laser light and measuring the time between emission and reception of the reflected pulses. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 2763)
the given area has been swept using a system comprised of multiple echo sounder transducers attached to booms deployed from the survey vessel.
the depth was determined by using an instrument that compares electromagnetic signals. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 1571)
the depth was determined by applying mathematical techniques to photographs. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 3791)
the depth was determined by using instruments placed aboard an artificial satellite. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 4509)
the depth was determined by using levelling techniques to find the elevation of the point relative to a datum. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 2741)
the given area was determined to be free from navigational dangers to a certain depth by towing a side-scan-sonar. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5248, 4710) [415.2]
the sounding was determined from a bottom model constructed using a computer.

Attribute.Name: Textual description
Attribute.Indication: the string encodes the file name of an external text file that contains the text in English.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'textual description' indicates whether a text file containing text extracted from, for example, relevant pilot books or navigational publications is available
Attribute.Condition: For CTNARE and PRCARE objects, at least one of attributes INFORM or TXTDSC must be encoded. For S-57 Edition 3.1.1 ARCSLN, ASLXIS and NEWOBJ objects, and RESARE objects with CATREA=27 or 28, at least one of attributes INFORM or TXTDSC must be encoded.

Attribute.Name: Tidal stream - panel values
Attribute.Indication: The direction in degrees and velocity in knots are encoded in pairs. Each value separated by a comma.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'Tidal stream - panel values' encodes the identification of the reference station with reference water level and the direction of the flow and the springs rate from 6 hours before to 6 hours after high water (HW) or low water (LW) at the reference station, at hourly intervals. The relationship to a reference station is encoded using a collection object.

Attribute.Name: Tide stream - time series values
Attribute.Indication: The direction in degrees and velocity in knots are encoded in pairs. Each value separated by a comma.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'Tidal stream, current - time series values ' encodes values for a direction and velocity time series.

Attribute.Name: Tidal - accuracy of water level
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'Tide - accuracy of water level ' encodes the accuracy of the water level, to the confidence level of 95%.

Attribute.Name: Tidal - high and low water values
Attribute.Indication: Dates/times and heights are to be encoded in pairs, each value separated by a comma. The date/time should be encoded using 4 digits for the calendar year (CCYY), 2 digits for the month (MM) (eg April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD), separated by a capital T from the hour (hh) and minutes (mm) which should each be encoded using 2 digits. This conforms to ISO 8601: 1988. Seconds should not be used. The height should be given in metres (xx.x) with a resolution of 0.1 metre.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'tide - high and low water values' encodes information on the times and heights of high and low waters for each day of the duration of the time series.

Attribute.Name: Tide - method of Tidal prediction
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'Tide - method of tidal prediction' encodes the various methods of tidal prediction.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: simplified harmonic method of tidal prediction
ExpectedValue.Definition: prediction of tidal heights by combining a simplified set of harmonic constituents into a single time/height curve.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: full harmonic method of tidal prediction
ExpectedValue.Definition: prediction of tidal heights by combining a complete set of harmonic constituents into a single time/height curve.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: time and height difference non-harmonic method
ExpectedValue.Definition: prediction of high and low water times and heights by modification of the high and low water times and heights of a known time/height curve.

Attribute.Name: Tide - time and height differences
Attribute.Indication: time difference in hours and minutes: ± hhmm (according to ISO 8106: 1988); height difference: metres (preceded with - if negative value); rate difference: knots (preceded with - if negative value)
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'tide - time and height differences' encodes the time and tidal height or tidal stream rate difference comparative to a reference station. The format is the same for tides and tidal streams, with height difference being replaced by rate difference. The relation to a reference station is encoded by the use of a collection object. The attribute is used to contain the identification of the reference station and , encoded in triplets, mean time difference (+ or -), height or rate difference for mean high water or mean high rate (preceded with - if negative value), height or rate difference for mean low water or mean low rate (preceded with - if negative value), each value separated by a comma.

Attribute.Name: Tidal - time interval of values
Attribute.Indication: Unit: minutes; Resolution:
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'Tide, current - time interval of values ' encodes the interval between the values in any time series, e.g. tidal, current or other data.

Attribute.Name: Tide - time series values
Attribute.Indication: the height above or below (-ve) datum. Each value separated by a comma.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'tide - time series values' encodes the values of a time series.

Attribute.Name: Value of harmonic constituents
Attribute.Definition: Harmonic constituents are the harmonic elements in a mathematical expression for the tide producing force and in the corresponding formula for the tidal curve. Each constituent represents a periodic change or variation in the relative positions of the earth, moon and sun.
Attribute.Indication: the first is the number of columns (C, always 2) and the second is the number of rows (R). The next value(s) (C times) indicates the name(s) of the columns, and the next value(s) (R times) indicates the name(s) of the rows (ie constituents). Here after follow the values (C x R times) of amplitude and phase.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'tide - value of harmonic constituents' contains a 2 dimensional array of harmonic constituents.

Attribute.Name: Time end
Attribute.Indication: The 'time end' will consist of a date and a time separated by a capital T. The date should be encoded using 4 digits for the calendar year (CCYY), 2 digits for the month (MM) (e.g. April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). The time should be encoded using 2 digits for the hour (hh), 2 digits for the minutes (mm) and 2 digits for the seconds (ss). This conforms to ISO 8601: 1988.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'time end' indicates the end of a active period.

Attribute.Name: Time start
Attribute.Indication: The 'time start' will consist of a date and a time separated by a capital T. The date should be encoded using 4 digits for the calendar year (CCYY), 2 digits for the month (MM) (e.g. April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). The time should be encoded using 2 digits for the hour (hh), 2 digits for the minutes (mm) and 2 digits for the seconds (ss). This conforms to ISO 8601: 1988.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'time start' indicates the start of an active period.

Attribute.Name: Tint
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'tint' is used to indicate that a polygon should be filled with a given colour tint.

Attribute.Name: Topmark/daymark shape
Attribute.References: INT 1: IQ 9; M-4: 463.1 (for International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA systems only)

ExpectedValue.Definition: a solid figure generated by straight lines drawn from a fixed point (the vertex) to a circle in a plane not containing the vertex. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993, vol 2) cones are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities -IALA topmarks (lateral). point up is where the vertex points up.

a solid figure generated by straight lines drawn from a fixed point (the vertex) to a circle in a plane not containing the vertex. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993, vol 2) cones are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities -IALA topmarks (lateral). point up is where the vertex points down.

a body the surface of which is at all points equidistant from the centre. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary, 1993. vol 2). Spheres are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks (safe water).
two black spheres are commonly used as an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmark (isolated danger).

a solid geometrical figure generated by straight lines fixed in direction and describing with one of point a closed curve, especially a circle (in which case the figure is a circular cylinder, it's ends being parallel circles). (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2). cylinders are commonly used as an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks (lateral).
usually of rectangular shape made from timber or metal and used to provide a contrast with the natural background of a daymark. The actual daymark is often painted on the board.

having a shape or a cross-section like the capital letter X. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2). an x-shapeas an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmark should be 3 dimensional in shape. It is made of at least three crossed bars.
a cross with one vertical member and one horizontal member, i.e. similar in shape to the character '+'.
a solid contained by six equal squares; a regular hexahedron (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2). cube, point up is a cube standing on one of its vertexes.
2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices together in the centre.
2 cones, one above the other, with their bases together in the centre and their vertices pointing up and down.
a plane figure having four equal sides and equal opposite angles (two acute and two obtuse); an oblique equilateral parallelogram. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)
a bundle of rods or twigs. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 1.)
a bundle of rods or twigs. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 1.)
a flag mounted on a short pole.
a sphere located above a rhombus.
a plane figure with four right angles and four equal straight sides. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)

a plane figure with four right angles and four straight sides, opposite sides being parallel and equal in length with the two longer opposite sides are standing horizontally. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)

a plane figure with four right angles and four straight sides, opposite sides being parallel and equal in length with the two longer opposite sides are standing vertically. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)
a quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2), which stands on its longer parallel side.
a quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2), which stands on its shorter parallel side.
a figure having three angles and three sides. (New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)
a figure having three angles and three sides. (New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)
a perfectly round plane figure whose circumference is everywhere equidistant from its centre. (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 1)

ExpectedValue.Meaning: two upright crosses (one over the other)
ExpectedValue.Definition: two upright crosses, generally vertically disposed one above the other.
having a shape like the capital letter T.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: triangle pointing up over a circle
ExpectedValue.Definition: a triangle, vertex uppermost, located above a circle.
an upright cross located above a circle.
a rhombus located above a circle.

ExpectedValue.Meaning: circle over a triangle pointing up
ExpectedValue.Definition: a circle located over a triangle, vertex uppermost.
traffic flow in a general direction towards a port or similar destination.
traffic flow in a general direction away from a port or similar point of origin.
traffic flow in one general direction only.
traffic flow in two generally opposite directions.

Attribute.Name: Value of annual change in magnetic variation
Attribute.Definition: The annual change in magnetic variation values.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: minute ('), negative west; Resolution: 0.1'
Attribute.Remarks: A positive value, i.e. unsigned, indicates a change in an easterly direction and a negative value indicates a change in a westerly direction. Distinction: value of magnetic variation;
Attribute.Format: sxx.x; s: sign, negative values only

Attribute.Name: Value of depth contour
Attribute.Definition: The depth of a sea bottom contour.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the DUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the DUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 fm or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Remarks: Drying contours are indicated by a negative value.
Attribute.Format: sxxxxx.x; s: sign, negative values only.

Attribute.Name: Value of local magnetic anomaly
Attribute.Definition: The value of the deviation from the normal magnetic variation.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: minute ('); Resolution: 0.1'
Attribute.Remarks: The deviation is assumed to be positive and negative. The plus/minus character shall not be encoded.

Attribute.Name: Value of magnetic variation
Attribute.Definition: The magnetic variation value.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: degree (°), negative west. Resolution: 0.01 degree
Attribute.Remarks: A positive value, i.e. unsigned, indicates variation in an easterly direction and a negative value indicates variation in a westerly direction. Distinction: value of annual change in magnetic variation;
Attribute.Format: sxx.xx s: sign, negative values only.

Attribute.Name: Value of maximum range
Attribute.Definition: The extreme distance at which an object can be seen or a signal detected.
Attribute.References: INT 1: not specified; M-4: not specified;
Attribute.Indication: Unit: nautical mile (M); Resolution: 0.1 M
Attribute.Remarks: This attribute does not apply to lights where the attribute 'value of nominal range' should be used.

Attribute.Name: Value of nominal range
Attribute.Definition: The nominal range at which an object can be seen or a signal detected.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: nautical mile (M); Resolution: 0.1 M
Attribute.Remarks: The nominal range is normally the luminous range of a light in a homogeneous atmosphere in which the meteorological visibility is 10 sea miles. (IHO Hydrographic Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4218)

Attribute.Name: Value of sounding
Attribute.Definition: The value of the measurement of a sounding relative to the chart datum.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the DUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the DUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 fm or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Remarks: A drying height is indicated by a negative value.
Attribute.Format: sxxxxx.xx; s: sign, negative values only. Examples: 18.2 for a sounding of 18.2 metres. -2.4 for a drying height of 2.4 metres.
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for all MARCUL objects if they are under water. For WRECKS objects, at least one of attributes CATWRK or VALSOU must be encoded.

Attribute.Name: Vertical accuracy
Attribute.Definition: The best estimate of the vertical accuracy of heights, vertical distances and vertical clearances, excluding sounding measurements.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft

Attribute.Name: Vertical clearance
Attribute.Definition: The vertical clearance measured from the plane towards the object overhead.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Remarks: In the case of cables carrying high voltages an additional clearance of from 2 to 5 metres may be needed to avoid an electrical discharge. When known, the authorized safe clearance (known in the UK as the Safe Overhead Clearance) which is the physical clearance minus a safety margin shall be stated. (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). See also 'vertical clearance safe
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for BRIDGE objects over navigable water that are non-opening. Must be encoded for CBLOHD objects over navigable water if attribute VERCSA is not known. Must be encoded for CONVYR objects over navigable water. Must be encoded for PIPOHD objects over navigable water.

Attribute.Name: Vertical clearance, closed
Attribute.Definition: The vertical clearance of an object in closed condition (e.g. a closed lifting bridge) measured from the plane towards the object overhead.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for BRIDGE objects over navigable water that are opening.

Attribute.Name: Vertical clearance, open
Attribute.Definition: The vertical clearance of an object in opened condition (e.g.. an opened lifting bridge) measured from the plane towards the object overhead.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for BRIDGE objects over navigable water that are opening, with limited clearance when open.

Attribute.Name: Vertical clearance, safe
Attribute.Definition: The safe vertical clearance measured from the plane towards the object overhead.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Remarks: In the case of cables carrying high voltages, the quoted vertical clearance (VERCLR) may have to be reduced by 2-5m to avoid electrical discharge. When known, this authorized safe clearance (known in the UK as the Safe Overhead Clearance) which is the physical clearance minus a safety margin shall, be stated. (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). See also 'Vertical Clearance'.
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for CBLOHD objects over navigable water, or if this is unknown, encode attribute VERCLR.

Attribute.Name: Vertical datum
Attribute.Remarks: This attribute is used to specify the datum to which both heights (vertical datum, see S-57 Part 3) and soundings (sounding datum, see S-57 Part 3) are referred. When the vertical datum is unknown, such as water areas above locks, the value 'local datum' is to be used, and further details may be encoded using 'INFORM'. The 0.3m approximation quoted in the Aapproximate levels is somehow arbitrary and follows the British example of their definition for Aapproximate LAT.

ExpectedValue.Definition: (MLWS) - the average height of the low waters of spring tides. Also called spring low water. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3150)
(MLLWS) - the average height of lower low water springs at a place. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3146)

(MSL) - the average height of the surface of the sea at a tide station for all stages of the tide over a 19-year period, usually determined from hourly height readings measured from a fixed predetermined reference level. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3156)
an arbitrary level conforming to the lowest tide observed at a place, or some what lower.
(MLW) - the average height of all low waters at a place over a 19-year period. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3147)
an arbitrary level conforming to the lowest water level observed at a place at spring tides during a period of time shorter than 19 years. (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy)
an arbitrary level, usually within +-0.3m from that of mean low water springs (MLWS). (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy)

(ISLW) - an arbitrary tidal datum approximating the level of the mean of the lower low water at spring tides. Also called Indian tidal plane. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2427) A tidal datum approximating the lowest water level observed at a place, originated by G.H. Darwin for the tides of India at a level below MSL being equal to the sum of amplitudes of the harmonic constituents M2, S2, K1, and O1; usually below that of the lower low water at spring tides. Also called Indian tide plane. (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy).
an arbitrary level, approximating that of mean low water springs (MLWS). (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy)
an arbitrary level, usually within +-0.3m from that of lowest astronomical tide (LAT). (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy)
an arbitrary level approximating the lowest water level observed at a place, usually equivalent to the Indian spring low water (ISLW). (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy)
(MLLW) - the average height of the lower low waters at a place over a 19-year period. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3145)

an approximation of mean low water adopted as the reference level for a limited area, irrespective of better determinations at a later date. Used mostly in harbour and river engineering. Used in inland (non-tidal) waters. It is generally defined as a level which the daily mean water level would fall below less than 5% of the time and by no more than 0.2 metres during the navigation season. A single level surface is usually chosen as the low water datum for a whole lake. On a river, low water datum is a sloping surface which approximates the river surface at a low state. (Canadian Hydrographic Service)
an arbitrary level, usually within +-0.3m from that of mean low water (MLW). (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy)
an arbitrary level, usually within +-0.3m from that of mean lower low water (MLLW). (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy)
(MHW) - the average height of all high waters at a place over a 19-year period. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3141)
(MHWS) - the average height of the high waters of spring tides. Also called spring high water. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3144)

the highest level reached at a place by the water surface in one tidal cycle. Also called high tide. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2251). when used on inland (non-tidal) waters, it is generally defined as a level which the daily mean water level exceeds less than 5% of the time.
an arbitrary level, usually within +-0.3m from that of mean sea level (MSL). (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy)
an arbitrary level, approximating that of mean high water springs (MHWS). (Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy)
(MHHW) - the average height of higher high waters at a place over a 19-year period. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3140)
the level of low water springs near the time of an equinox.
(LAT) - the lowest tide level which can be predicted to occur under average meterological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2936)
an arbitrary datum defined by a local harbour authority, from which levels and tidal heights are measured by this authority.
(IGLD 1985) - a vertical reference system with its zero based on the mean water level at Rimouski/Pointe-au-Pere, Quebec over the period 1970 to 1988.
the average of all hourly water levels over the available period of record.
(LLWLT) - the average of the lowest low waters, one from each of 19 years of observations.
(HHWLT) - the average of the highest high waters, one from each of 19 years of observations.
an arbitrary level approximating the highest water level observed at a place, usually equivalent to the high water springs.
the highest tidal level which can be predicted to occur under average meteorological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2244).
Vertical Datum is not applicable

Attribute.Name: Vertical length
Attribute.Definition: The total vertical length of an object.
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 ft
Attribute.Remarks: For floating objects: the vertical distance from the surface of water to the highest point of that object. For fixed objects: the vertical dist ance from seabed or ground to the highest point of that object. For objects on top of other objects: the vertical distance from the lowest to the highest point of that object. Vertical length measurements do not require a datum.

Attribute.Name: Water level effect
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'water level effect' encodes the effect of the surrounding water on an object.
Attribute.Condition: Must be encoded for all MARCUL objects if they are under water.

ExpectedValue.Definition: partially covered and partially dry at high water.
not covered at high water under average meteorological conditions.
remains covered by water at all times under average meteorological conditions.

expression intended to indicate an area of a reef or other projection from the bottom of a body of water which periodically extends above and is submerged below the surface. Also referred to as dries or uncovers. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1111)
flush with, or washed by the waves at low water under average meteorological conditions. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 308)
an area periodically covered by flood water, excluding tidal waters. (Digital Geographic Information Standard - DIGEST 1.2)
resting or moving on the surface of a liquid without sinking (Concise Oxford Dictionary).

the horizontal movement of water associated with the rising tide. Flood streams generally set towards the shore, or in the direction of the tide progression. Also called flood, flood current or ingoing stream. (Adapted from IHO Dictioanry, S-32, 5th Edition)

the horizontal movement of water associated with falling tide. Ebb streams generally set seaward, or in the opposite direction to the tide progression. Also called ebb, ebb current or outgoing stream. (Adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition)
any other horizontal movement of water associated with tides, eg. rotary flow.

Attribute.Name: Positional accuracy units
Attribute.Remarks: This attribute encodes the units for positional accuracy which may be different from the unit for coordinates. The latter is specified at the dataset level in the COUN subfield of the DSPM record.

ExpectedValue.Definition: Positional accuracy is specified in metres (SI units of positional accuracy).
Positional accuracy is specified in degrees of arc.
Positional accuracy is specified in millimeters.
Positional accuracy is specified in feet (imperial units of positional accuracy).

a unit of distance originally equal to the length of a ship's anchor cable, but now generally considered to be about 600 feet. In the British Navy it is 608 feet, or exactly one-tenth of a nautical mile. In the United States Navy it is 720 feet but is infrequently used. Sometimes called cable length. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 589).

Attribute.Name: Object Class Definition
Attribute.Definition: Specifies the defining characteristics of a ‘new object’.
Attribute.Remarks: Identical definitions must be used for other instances of identical features being encoded. The wording for the attribute CLSDEF must be approved by TSMAD before use.

Attribute.Name: Object Class Name
Attribute.Definition: Specifies the descriptive name of a ‘new object’ feature object class.
Attribute.Remarks: All ‘new objects’ of the same class must share the same CLSNAM. The wording for the attribute CLSNAM must be approved by TSMAD before use.

Attribute.Name: Symbol Instruction
Attribute.Definition: This specifies the S-52 Presentation Library symbol instruction to be adopted in ECDIS for the new object class (as specified in the S-52 Symbol Library - Addendum to S-52 Presentation Library).
Attribute.Remarks: The string for the attribute SYMINS must be approved by CSMWG and TSMAD before use. Point, simple and complex lines, area or text symbol instructions may be specified. If SYMINS is not populated, a default symbol is provided. Symbol instructions are explained in the Presentation Library Users’ Manual, Part A, sections 3.3 and 7 "DESCRIPTION OF THE SYMBOLOGY INSTRUCTIONS". Note that the separator between two instructions is the character ';' (semi-colon). SYMINS = "SY(CHINFO11);LS(DASH,2,CHMGD)"

Attribute.Name: Information in national language
Attribute.LocalName: 用国家语言表示的信息
Attribute.Indication: Text (c...): Textual information in national language characters
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'information in national language' encodes any textual information about an object using a specified national language. This attribute should be used, for example, to hold the information that is shown on paper charts by cautionary and explanatory notes.
Attribute.Format: up to 300 characters may be included in this string.

Attribute.Name: Object name in national language
Attribute.LocalName: 用国家语言表示的物标名称
Attribute.Indication: Name of object (c...):string of national language characters
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'object name in national language' encodes the individual name of an object in the specified national language.

Attribute.Name: Pilot district in national character set
Attribute.LocalName: 用国家语言表示的引航区
Attribute.Indication: Pilot district (c...):string of national language characters
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'pilot district in national language' encodes the pilot district for which a pilot station is responsible in the specified national language.

Attribute.Name: Text string in national language
Attribute.LocalName: 用国家语言表示的文本串

Attribute.Name: Textual description in national language
Attribute.LocalName: 用国家语言表示的正文
Attribute.Indication: the string encodes the file name of an external text file that contains the text in a national language.
Attribute.Remarks: The attribute 'textual descrition in national language' indicates whether a text file containing text extracted from, for example, relevant pilot books or navigational publications is available.

Attribute.Name: Horizontal datum
Attribute.Remarks: All necessary information for conversion of geographic coordinates from most of the Geodetic Datums in the above list to WGS-84 is contained in the "User's Handbook on Datum Transformations involving WGS-84", prepared by the US Defense Mapping Agency and which is available from the IHB as IHO Publication S-60 (English and French Versions), along with an associated standard datum transformation software on floppy disk called "MADTRAN". The resulting latitude and longitude offsets can be encoded in the attribute SHIPAM.

Attribute.Name: Positional accuracy
Attribute.Indication: Unit: defined in the PUNI subfield of the DSPM record, e.g. metre (m); Resolution: 0.1 m or 0.1 mm

ExpectedValue.Definition: the position(s) was(were) determined by the operation of making measurements for determining the relative position of points on, above or beneath the earth's surface. Survey implies a regular, controlled survey of any date. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5195 and IHO Chart Specifications, M-4, 175.2)
survey data does not exist or is very poor. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5732)
position data is of a very poor quality. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5732)

a position that is considered to be less than third-order accuracy, but is generally considered to be within 30.5 metres of its correct geographic location. Also may apply to an object whose position does not remain fixed. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 213, 3967, and IHO Specifications, M-4, 424.1)
an object whose position has been reported but which is considered to be doubtful.
an object's position obtained from questionable or unreliable data.
an object whose position has been reported and its position confirmed by some means other than a formal survey such as an independent report of the same object.
an object whose position has been reported and its position has not been confirmed.
the most probably position of an object determined from incomplete data or data of questionable accuracy. (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 3960)
a position that is of a known value, such as the position of an anchor berth or other defined object.
a position that is computed from data.
